\begin_layout Subsection*
Non-competes, spinoffs and innovation / growth
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Observations:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Non-competes very common among senior executives (70.2%, Garmaise 2011),
 electrical engineers (50%, Marx 2011), and 
\emph on
especially 
\emph default
common among companies receiving investments from VC firms (90%, Kaplan
 & Stroemberg 2003).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
non-competes solve a hold-up problem but also can reduce the dissemination
 of knowledge, reallocation of workers to better-matched firms, and reduce
 competition (even if there is no knowledge spillover).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
non-competes are heavily enforced in some states (e.g., MA, TX) but very weakly
 enforced in other states (e.g., CA).
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Question: 
\series default
What is the effect of non-competes on growth, business / labor-market dynamism,
 and welfare? What is the optimal non-compete enforcement policy? 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Growth and welfare:
\series default
 pretty clear reason why this matters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Labor market dynamism: 
\series default
Would be interesting to see what the prediction of the model is for labor-market
 dynamism and see if that helps to explain the decline documented in e.g.
 Hyattt & Spletzer IZA 2013.
 However, as they document, the decline in hires and separations has been
 driven largely by a decline in 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

short-term jobs
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and is largest in recessions.
 Not sure how this squares with the secular increase in the usage of non-compete
s.
 
\end_layout

