\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

non-poaching
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 agreements with other firms in the absence of non-compete enforcement.
 This implies: (1) we have to be careful about how we model the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

no enforcement
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 regime; (2) since this practice appears to be somewhat common in Silicon
 Valley, even ignoring brain drain, the fact that 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Answer: need a 
\series bold
general equilibrium model 
\series default
of endogenous growth through R&D, with knowledge spillovers over to R&D
 employees.
 Especially in light of Marx et.
 al.
 2015 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Brain drain
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, it's plausible that enforcing non-competes in a particular region leads
 to underperformance largely due to brain drain, i.e.
 the effect of not enforcing non-competes in certain regions is to depress
 national output, but also shift it to regions where non-competes are not
 enforced.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Model based on Akcigit & Kerr 2017, which is based on Klette & Kortum 2004.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
So far modeling ONE aspect of this - people leaving to form competing startups.
 Still, works in the same direction - the more ppl you employ in R&D, the
 more competition you will have.
 This lowers the investment in R&D, because you want to prevent this spillover
 of knowledge.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Many others that could be added in principle, each with their own parameters
 to identify.
 This is the simplest, I think.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Want to use model to evaluate: 
\end_layout

